bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Fund for the Advancement of Education (TFAE) was established in 1951 to support new and experimental programs at all levels of formal education. The five areas to which TFAE focused its resources were: the equalization of educational opportunity; improvements in curricula; clarification of the functions of educational institutions; improvement of educational management and financing; and the improvement of teaching. TFAE operated for over a decade. It ceased funding new projects in the late 1960s.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition note
acqinfo.p: Ford Foundation archive was deposited at RAC in 2011. Ford Foundation records, correspondence, reports, program files and officers papers were transferred to, and accessioned by, RAC beginning in 2011. Accessions continue as necessary.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use note
userestrict.p: Ford Foundation holds title, copyright and literary rights in the collection, in so far as it holds them.

The Rockefeller Archive Center has authority to grant permission to cite and publish material from the collection for scholarly purposes. Permission to publish extensive excerpts, or material in its entirety, will be referred to the Ford Foundation.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access note
accessrestrict.p: Records more than 10 years old are open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC.
Completion of a use agreement is required prior to providing scholarly access. See RAC Head of Reference (or applicable designee) for details.

Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation note
prefercite.p: Information regarding the Rockefeller Archive Center's preferred elements and forms of citation can be found at http://www.rockarch.org/research/citations.php

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The TFAE files are arranged in 5 series:
I. Board of Directors and Administrative Files. II. Grant Awardees - Educational Institutions. III. Grant Awardees - Multi-Institutional (not Fund Administered). IV. Conferences. V. Publications.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Primarily consists of: Administrative files, Grant files, correspondence and reports, Board of Directors records, financial records, and documentation of conferences and publications.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: The series is comprised of five sub-series: Grant Files; General Correspondence; Fund Administered Projects; Grantee Award Authorization Files; and Grantee Financial Reports on Expenditures. The sub-series are primarily arranged alphabetically by educational institution.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The series Grant Awardees – Educational Institutions is comprised of records relating to the Fund's support of "promising experiments," demonstrations or pilot programs in colleges, universities, public schools or other educational institutions.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The Grant Files sub-series consists of files for awarded projects. Documents include grant proposals and background attachments, grant award letters, press releases, and progress and/or final report(s) submitted to TFAE. Projects of note in the sub-series regard: desegregation and equalization of education; education in the [former] U.S.S.R.; and educational television.

scopecontent.p: The sub-series Equalization of Education pertains to the TFAE funded work of Harry S. Ashmore and of the Southern Education Reporting Service concerning segregation in public schools. The survey reports were published in 1953 and 1954, shortly before the Brown vs. Board of Education ruling.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The Faculty Fellowship Program was created in 1951 to broaden and strengthen the qualifications of college teachers in the United States. The Program was administered by the American Council of Learned Societies and supported the exploration of the Humanities, Social Sciences, and Natural Sciences. The sub-series consists of administrative files and fellowship awardee files and contains: resumes, transcripts, letters of reference, and fellowship award letters.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The High-School Teachers Fellowship Program sub-series consists of information on each applicant and their school. The awardee files are arranged in chronological order by the academic year awarded, then alphabetically by the fellow's surname. Also included are files on policy and procedures, statistics and reports. The majority of these files are confidential in nature as the resumes contain financial and personal information. Box 18 contains grant file cards of the Fellowship winners.
